'''Cecil Pitt''' was a [[Tyneside]] songwriter, who lived in the early nineteenth century
==Brief details==
'''Cecil Pitt''' (lived c1812) was a [[Tyneside]] songwriter, who, according to the information given by [[John Bell (Junior)|John Bell]] in his [[(Geordie) Rhymes of Northern Bards by John Bell Junior| Rhymes of Northern Bards]] published in 1812, has the song "The Newcastle Signs" attributed to his name.

The song is not written in [[Geordie dialect words|Geordie dialect]] but is definitely local to Newcastle. It was sung at Newcastle Theatre Royal by Mr Scrifen on 4 June 1806

The same song with the same comments appears on page 89 of <U+201C>[[The Tyne Songster by W & T Fordyce - 1840|The Tyne Songster]]" published by [[W & T Fordyce (publishers)|W & T Fordyce]] in 1840 and in "[[Marshall's Collection of Songs, Comic, Satirical 1827| Marshall's Collection of Songs]]" published by [[John Marshall (Newcastle publisher and printer)|John Marshall]] in 1827.

Nothing more appears to be known of this person, or their life
